text: Historical note:  During the days of slavery, Southern elite in the United States had an ambition to annex several territories, such as Mexico, Central America, Venezuela, and Colombia to create new slave states, thus creating a "Golden Circle" around the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean.  This vast increase in the number of slave states would give indefinite power to the South, and was therefore naturally never given serious thought.    Is it related to this movie?  Doubtful, seeing as the Kingsmen (and therefore the Statesmen) were not created until the early 20th century.  But now you know a little bit more than you did before.

text: There's not a Matthew Vaughn movie (that's not under a major studio) that I didn't like.  His tone has always been slightly tongue in cheek and not taking the whole business too seriously,  But he's never disrespected the medium either.  I sense that he really likes the magic of movie making.    Kingsman (the first one) was full of his trademark humor, flare, and clever use of music as part of a character.  Judging by this trailor, Kingsman 2 seems to be a joy ride (really, "Statesman" and "Kingsman", LOL!).    Mr. Vaugh is producing and directing "I AM Pilgrim" now.   The book is one of my all time fave thrillers.  I think it is in good hands to have Vaughn attached to it.

text: One of my favorite parts of The Secret Service was its loyalty, or rather adherence, to Arthurian legend. It was said that Merlin himself gave the Knights of The Round Table and King Arthur weapons such as Excalibur, similar to the gadgets Merlin shows Eggsy in the Movie. In this legend, Merlin bewitches a sword into a stone, declaring that whomever puled it out would be made the King. This is once again similar to the trials Merlin executes to choose who is accepted into the secret service. Finally, proceeding the battle at Camlin, it was said that King Arthur and his knights dwelt under a hill, waiting to be called upon to save the world, much like the Kingsmen did in the movie.

text: I was extremely excited to see the new Kingsman movie and I rushed to the theater on opening night. I almost never do that. Of course, there were funny jokes and great fights, but I felt like this movie was made to serve the liquor industries propaganda over the rising use of marijuana. I am a personally no user of liquor or marijuana and I can clearly see the agenda being pushed from the liquor industry, as Halle Berry tells Channing Tatum - "From now on, I suggest you stick with booze."  I feel like the first movie was a lot purer from every angle than the second and just because it got a lot of admirations, I think some capital forces decided to join in on the party and sell their ideas of "what's right and wrong" by sponsoring the movie and having "the lovely cast" do some propaganda on their behalf, which I find disgusting.   The more I observe, the more I am convinced how Hollywood is just trying to push agendas from people with money and I am not talking about a simple product placement of cars, watches and etc. I am talking about some serious social issues that affect many and it seems that Hollywood's agenda is to continue to brainwash "the zombies" with lobbyist's propaganda.    But hey, this is just my 2 cents...

text: Only just viewed this second Kingsman movie and so sorry I paid for it! It's okay but not a patch on the first movie. My suspicions that those behind the original might have lost the plot were sadly confirmed. The original beauty of Kingsman. Its basic English base and style and the pace of the original has been lost. They might have had a plot where the Kingsmen had to operate in the USA but creating Statesmen and the often ludicrous situations and wasted storyline distractions that arose forced me to switch off after trying hard to stay with the movie beyond the final quarter.  Some doubtless love it but for me a movie crime has been committed and the main characters have been woefully wasted.
